## 4. Example `AGENTS.md` Routing Rules

Use this style:

```md
# AGENTS.md

## Root behavior

Before making changes, understand the relevant project area.
Prefer small, targeted changes.
Do not invent architecture that is not present in the codebase.
When uncertain, inspect files before answering.

## Rule loading

Use the following routing rules:

| Task type | Additional rule files |
|---|---|
| Backend service, controllers, service layer, repositories | `docs/rules/backend-rules.md` |
| API request/response, OpenAPI, GraphQL, contracts | `docs/rules/api-rules.md` |
| Database schema, migrations, queries, repositories | `docs/rules/data-rules.md` |
| Frontend UI, routes, components, state management | `docs/rules/frontend-rules.md` |
| Docker, Kubernetes, Terraform, CI/CD, deployment | `docs/rules/infra-rules.md` |
| Unit/integration/e2e tests | `docs/rules/testing-rules.md` |
| README, design docs, ADRs, project documentation | `docs/rules/docs-rules.md` |

## Workflow routing

If the user asks to analyze, understand, dissect, reverse-engineer, or map the project,
use the `analyze-project` workflow.

If the user asks to update, sync, refresh, or generate documentation,
use the `update-docs` workflow.

If the user asks to review code, use the `code-review` workflow.

## Documentation policy

When a change affects public behavior, APIs, configuration, data model, deployment,
architecture, or operational behavior, update relevant documentation in the same change.

Before finishing, state one of:

- Documentation updated: `<files>`
- Documentation not needed because: `<reason>`
```

## 5. Should You Use `xxx/rules.md`?

Yes. This is the right pattern.

But do not create too many rules too early. You want enough separation to route well, but not so much fragmentation that agents miss context.

| Rule file           |                   Keep? | Why                                                   |
| ------------------- | ----------------------: | ----------------------------------------------------- |
| `backend-rules.md`  |                     Yes | Common for Java/Spring/FastAPI/service projects       |
| `frontend-rules.md` | Yes, if frontend exists | UI has different conventions                          |
| `api-rules.md`      |                     Yes | API contracts deserve explicit discipline             |
| `data-rules.md`     |                     Yes | DB/schema/query changes are high-risk                 |
| `infra-rules.md`    |                     Yes | Docker/K8s/Terraform/CI/CD need different constraints |
| `testing-rules.md`  |                     Yes | Prevents agents from skipping tests                   |
| `docs-rules.md`     |                     Yes | Centralizes doc update expectations                   |
| `security-rules.md` |  Optional separate file | Use if auth/permissions are substantial               |
| `ai-rules.md`       |                Optional | Use if this is an AI/agent/RAG/LLM project            |

For your projects, I would use:

```text
docs/rules/
├── backend-rules.md
├── api-rules.md
├── data-rules.md
├── infra-rules.md
├── testing-rules.md
├── docs-rules.md
└── ai-agent-rules.md
```

## 6. Project Understanding Docs: Are 3 Files Enough?

You proposed:

1. Tech stack, frameworks, versions
2. Business idea and features
3. APIs and call stack flows

These are necessary, but not sufficient.

For serious project analysis, you need at least these dimensions:

| File                       | Purpose                                             | Why it matters                                  |
| -------------------------- | --------------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------------- |
| `00-index.md`              | Map of all project-intel docs                       | Gives the agent a navigation entry point        |
| `01-business-domain.md`    | Business idea, users, features, domain vocabulary   | Prevents code-only understanding                |
| `02-tech-stack.md`         | Languages, frameworks, versions, package managers   | Helps with correct commands and conventions     |
| `03-architecture.md`       | Modules, layers, bounded contexts, major components | Needed for design-level reasoning               |
| `04-api-surface.md`        | REST/GraphQL/events/CLI endpoints                   | Shows external contracts                        |
| `05-call-flows.md`         | Request lifecycle and important execution paths     | Critical for debugging and feature work         |
| `06-data-model.md`         | Entities, tables, migrations, schemas, ownership    | Needed for persistence and business correctness |
| `07-runtime-deployment.md` | Local run, Docker, env vars, cloud resources        | Needed to actually operate the app              |
| `08-testing-quality.md`    | Test types, commands, coverage gaps, fixtures       | Prevents unsafe edits                           |
| `09-security-auth.md`      | AuthN/AuthZ, roles, secrets, permissions            | Critical for real systems                       |
| `10-observability-ops.md`  | Logs, metrics, traces, alerts, runbooks             | Needed for production thinking                  |
| `11-open-questions.md`     | Ambiguities, TODOs, risks, suspected issues         | Prevents hallucinated certainty                 |

So I would not do only 3. I would do **12 small files**.

## 7. Minimal vs Serious Version

| Version    |       Files | Best for                                                       |
| ---------- | ----------: | -------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Minimal    |   3–4 files | Small toy app, prototype                                       |
| Practical  |     8 files | Real local project with backend/frontend/db                    |
| Serious    |    12 files | Production-like project, interview portfolio, AI agent project |
| Enterprise | 15–25 files | Large mono-repo, many services, infra, compliance              |

For your goal — AI architect / senior engineer / big tech prep — use the **serious 12-file version**.

